    <td width=640 class="tdmain"> 
      <!-- PAGE CONTENTS STARTS HERE -->
      <h4>Simulation of Array Data for Hybridization-based Gene Expression Analysis</h4>
      <br>
      <P> DNA-array techniques are evolving more and more rapidly in recent years. 
          Here at the <A href="http://www.molgen.mpg.de">MPI for Molecular Genetics </A>
          we use micro- and macro-arrays 
          for <A href="http://www.molgen.mpg.de/~lh_bioinf/projects/statistics/">gene expression analysis</A> and 
          <A href="http://www.molgen.mpg.de/~ag_onf">oligonucleotide fingerpringing</A>. </P>
      <P> Major problems in this research area are the reliability and reproducibility 
        of data produced by DNA-array experiments. For this reason we set up a simulation 
        tool for array experiments. Parameters which might be critical during 
        the experimental procedure (like the spot position, spot shape or background 
        noise) can be varied. </P>
      <P> The use of the simulation and subsequent data analysis is described in  
          Wierling et al.: '<I>Simulation of DNA array hybridization experiments
          and evaluation of critical parameters during subsequent image and data analysis</I>',
          BMC Bioinformatics 2002, 3:29. 
          [<a href="http://www.biomedcentral.com/1471-2105/3/29/abstract">abstract</a>]</P>
      <P> Simulated images and corresponding signal data used in the paper mentioned 
        above can be downloaded here: </P>
      <P> 
      <ul>
        <li>Spot shifting (8 images;
		[<A HREF="RandomSpotShift/TIF/RandomSpotShift_TIFs.tar.gz">
		TIF images</A>],
		[<A HREF="RandomSpotShift/ahd/RandomSpotShift_inputData.tar.gz">
		input data</A>]) 
        <li>Pin shifting (6 images;
		[<A HREF="PinShift/TIF/PinShift_TIFs.tar.gz">
		TIF images</A>],
		[<A HREF="PinShift/ahd/PinShift_inputData.tar.gz">
		input data</A>])
        <li>Crater and plateau spots (11 images;
		[<A HREF="Crater/TIF/Crater_TIFs.tar.gz">
		TIF images</A>],
		[<A HREF="Crater/ahd/Crater_inputData.tar.gz">
		input data</A>])                
        <li>Global background noise (3 images;
		[<A HREF="GlobalBG/TIF/GlobalBG_TIFs.tar.gz">
		TIF images</A>],
		[<A HREF="GlobalBG/ahd/GlobalBG_inputData.tar.gz">
		input data</A>])
        <li>Local background noise (8 images;
		[<A HREF="LocalBG/TIF/LocalBG_TIFs.tar.gz">
		TIF images</A>],
		[<A HREF="LocalBG/ahd/LocalBG_inputData.tar.gz">
		input data</A>])
        <li>Simulated expression test data: (each 6 images)<BR>
		&nbsp;control ([<A HREF="ExpressionTest/TIF/Control.tar.gz">
		TIF images</A>],
		[<A HREF="ExpressionTest/ahd/Control_inputData.tar.gz">
		input data</A>)];
		treatment ([<A HREF="ExpressionTest/TIF/Treatment.tar.gz">
		TIF images</A>],
		[<A HREF="ExpressionTest/ahd/Treatment_inputData.tar.gz">
		input data</A>])
      </ul>
      <p>
	      The input data files (tab-delimited flat-files with the 
              file-extension '.ahd') contain the data, which were used
	      as input data for the corresponding images. The meaning
	      of the columns is as follows:

	      <DL>
	      <DT>x_grid, y_grid:</DT>
	      <DD>spot-position in a 240 * 240 grid; origin of the 
                  grid is the upper left.</DD><P>

	      <DT>x_pixel, y_pixel:</DT>
	      <DD>position of the spot-center in pixel coordinates
                  (in sub-pixel resolution); origin is the upper left.</DD><P>

	      <DT>intensity:</DT>
	      <DD>hybridization signal intensity (including the background),
                  that was used for the simulation. (for the expression test
                  the intensity of interest is given by 'intensity' - 
                  'background')</DD><P>

	      <DT>background:</DT>
	      <DD>only the background intensity.</DD><P>

	      <DT>id:</DT>
	      <DD>identifier of the clone.</DD><P>

	      <DT>duplicate:</DT>
	      <DD>duplicate number for multiple spotted clones.</DD><P>

	      </DL>

	      <HR>
	    <P>For further information please contact 
	    <A href="mailto:wierling@molgen.mpg.de">Christoph Wierling</A>.
	    </P>
      </p>
    </td>
